     <div class="bd"> 
      <ul class="newsNav"> 
       <li class="active" data-type="both">英汉对照<i></i></li> 
       <li data-type="cn">译文<i></i></li> 
       <li data-type="en">原文<i></i></li> 
      </ul> 
      <div class="newsCon"> 
       <div class="all"> 
        <p class="en"> <img src="http://s3-ec.buzzfed.com/static/enhanced/terminal05/2012/9/19/10/enhanced-buzz-790-1348064494-7.jpg" /> </p>
        <p class="en">Music fandom usually erupts out of love. But sometimes we have connections to artists that emerge not as a romance, but as a struggle to understand an incredible musical force in our lives. For me, that force is Madonna.</p>
        <p class="cn">音乐粉丝圈通常爆发的爱。但有时我们需要艺术家的出现不是一个浪漫的关系，但作为一个努力去理解，在我们的生活中一个令人难以置信的音乐力量。对我来说，这是麦当娜的力量。</p>
        <p class="en">It’s complicated. Take “Vogue,” for instance.</p>
        <p class="cn">这很复杂。以“时尚，”为例。</p>
        <p class="en"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=GuJQSAiODqI" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="cn"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=gujqsaiodqi" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="en">“Vogue” is a classic. Madonna asserts, over those icy strings and shimmering drums, that she has the key to being fabulous, and it’s her unshakeable poise that sells her advice as eternally groundbreaking. If you were not cool and interesting before, the act of listening to “Vogue” makes you so. No wonder there are so many viral videos of young kids voguing to “Vogue”: they knew Madonna could directly inject them with style beyond their years.</p>
        <p class="cn">“时尚”是一个典型的。麦当娜说，在那些冰冷的字符串和闪烁的鼓，她已经是难以置信的关键，这是她的不可动摇的自信，卖她的建议是永恒的开创性。如果你以前不酷和有趣，倾听“时尚”让你如此。难怪有那么多的病毒性视频孩子表演“时尚”：他们知道麦当娜可以直接注入与风格超越年龄的。</p>
        <p class="en"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=p7xooONFtso" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="cn"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=p7xooonftso" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="en"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=I8XDo4lsa10" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="cn"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=i8xdo4lsa10" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="en">It’s also no wonder that the kids dancing to the video seem gay, and that the song has been a particularly inspiring anthem for gay people like me. “Vogue” was heavily influenced by the voguing dance style that came out of ‘80s queer ball culture and that was featured in the documentary <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.youtube.com/movie?v=a70ZXs5SnNM&amp;feature=mv_sr" target="_blank"><i>Paris is Burning</i></a> . There are subtle codes of queerness embedded in “Vogue’s” DNA, particularly in its emphasis on glamour and extravagance.</p>
        <p class="cn">这也难怪孩子们跳舞的视频似乎是同性恋，和这首歌是同性恋的人喜欢我特别鼓舞人心的歌。“时尚”是由voguing舞蹈风格的说出来，80年代酷儿球文化，是特色的纪录片， <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.youtube.com/movie?v=a70zxs5snnm&amp;feature=mv_sr" target="_blank">paris is burning</a> 严重影响。还有，嵌入在“时尚的”dna微妙的代码，尤其是对魅力和奢侈的强调。</p>
        <p class="en">But that’s also where there’s a problem. Most of the people who invented vogueing were poor black and Latino queers. Is “Vogue” just inspired by gay culture, or is it appropriated? Even the creator of <i>Paris is Burning</i> , Jennie Livingston, was sued by some of her subjects due to disputes over compensation. When Malcolm McLaren wrote a song influenced by the same ball culture (and predating “Vogue”), he featured Willie Ninja, one of the original voguers.</p>
        <p class="cn">但这也有一个问题。大多数人谁发明了vogueing穷黑人和拉丁裔同性恋。“时尚”只是受到同性恋文化，或者是适当的？即使是巴黎的创造者是燃烧，珍妮利文斯顿，是因纠纷赔偿她的一些受试者起诉。当马尔科姆迈凯轮写了一首歌，由相同的球文化的影响（和之前的“时尚”），他以威利的忍者，一个原始的voguers。</p>
        <p class="en"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=a9KDmJQjS_0" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="cn"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=a9kdmjqjs_0" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="en">Madonna did not include any original voguers in her video. Madonna fans would say that this is beside the point. With the song “Vogue,” Madonna has sneakily inserted a part of gay culture in the mainstream. Malcolm McLaren’s song didn’t accomplish that. Madonna is a bridge between cultures, they’d suggest, and that’s all she needs to accomplish. When there is so little gay culture visible in the wider culture, it is difficult to argue against this point of view. Without “Vogue,” most people wouldn’t know anything about voguing.</p>
        <p class="cn">麦当娜不包括任何原始voguers她的视频。麦当娜的球迷会说这不是重点。这首歌“时尚，”麦当娜偷偷插在主流的同性恋文化的一部分。马尔科姆迈凯轮的歌没有完成。麦当娜是不同文化之间的一座桥梁，他们会建议，这是所有她需要完成。当有这么少的同性恋文化可以在更广泛的文化，很难反驳这种观点。没有“时尚，“多数人不知道任何关于表演。</p>
        <p class="en">Madonna has been inspired by queers since the beginning of her career. She had some of her first performances at the Paradise Garage, a major club for New York’s gay community in the ‘70s and ‘80s. During this time, Keith Haring, the gay artist most known for his geometric, graffiti-inspired paintings, was <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.gwarlingo.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Haring_Polaroid-with-Madonna-Juxtapoz.jpg" target="_blank">one of her close friends</a> . In one early breakout performance in 1984, Madonna wore a Haring-designed outfit when she sang at his Paradise Garage birthday party:</p>
        <p class="cn">麦当娜一直受到同性恋者因为她职业生涯的开始。她有她的第一场在天堂车库，在70年代和80年代纽约的同性恋社区的一个大俱乐部。在这段时间里，基思哈林，同性恋艺术家最出名的几何，涂鸦灵感的绘画作品，是 <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.gwarlingo.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/haring_polaroid-with-madonna-juxtapoz.jpg" target="_blank">one of her close friends</a> 。在一个早期的突破表现在1984，麦当娜穿着哈林设计衣服当她唱他的天堂车库的生日聚会：</p>
        <p class="en"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=nRlOyktvKL0" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="cn"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=nrloyktvkl0" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="en">And in her videos and concerts she has presented alternative sexualities long before Katy Perry thought it was “so wrong” to try it. The video for “Justify My Love” was banned for showing what today would amount to a comically tame amount of same-sex kissing and role-playing. Although the term “gay icon” has become a meaningless term, if there is a person for whom it still fits, Madonna is it.</p>
        <p class="cn">在她的视频和音乐会，她提出了替代性行为之前很久，凯蒂派瑞认为这是“尝试错误”。视频：“证明我的爱”是禁止显示什么今天将达到一个滑稽的驯服的量的同性接吻和角色扮演。尽管“***恋”已经成为一个毫无意义的词，如果有人仍然适合人，麦当娜是。</p>
        <p class="en"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=Np_Y740aReI" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="cn"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=np_y740arei" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="en">Queers have responded. Drop a Madonna song at a gay club, and watch the hands rise up. For many of us, there is a joy in this sense of ownership: Madonna is ours in a way that other artists aren’t. Madonna remembers us, and we remember her C and that’s perhaps the strongest identifier of what a gay icon is. Realizing that everyone at a club feels pretty much the same way you do about an artist can be a powerful thing. Even now, when parts of the wider culture still argue that homosexuals are confused or unnatural, there is something reassuring and satisfying about the predictability C the naturalness C of hands rising in the air when a Madonna song plays. Communally dancing to a sympathetic diva can be close to bliss.</p>
        <p class="cn">同性恋者的反应。在一个同性恋俱乐部麦当娜的歌滴，看手起来。对我们许多人来说，这是有归属感的快乐：麦当娜以一种其他艺术家的图画。麦当娜记得我们是我们的，我们记得她C这也许是最强的一个同性恋图标是什么标识符。实现在一个俱乐部的每个人都感到非常相同的方式对一个艺术家你可以是一个强大的东西。即使现在，当部分的更广泛的文化仍然认为同性恋是困惑或不自然的，有关于自然C手在空中升起时，麦当娜的歌中的可预测性C放心和满意的东西。集体舞同情的女主角可以接近幸福。</p>
        <p class="en"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=EDwb9jOVRtU" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="cn"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=edwb9jovrtu" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="en">But even with all of this, I’m not sure I love her. As a gay man, I sometimes feel like I’ve been drafted into liking Madonna by the circumstances of my sexuality. Madonna is not a particularly warm artist. Madonna has never made me cry, as Kylie’s “All the Lovers” unexpectedly did to me one day recently.</p>
        <p class="cn">但尽管如此，我不确定我爱她。作为一个同性恋，我有时觉得我一直喜欢麦当娜起草的我的性取向的情况下。麦当娜不是一个特别温暖的艺术家。麦当娜从未使我哭泣，当凯莉的“所有”“竟然对我做的最近的一天。</p>
        <p class="en"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=frv6FOt1BNI" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="cn"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=frv6fot1bni" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="en">It’s cheap comparing female artists, but I think, in this case, it makes sense. Kylie exudes everything in “All the Lovers” that Madonna withholds: forgiveness, warmth, love. And this is a definite personal preference, but I love when strength grows out of a place of sadness or weakness. Kylie is building a case for hope among the hopeless; Madonna tells me to be confident. Madonna is powerful and strong C a role model for all women (and many men). But she’s so in control she doesn’t even really need us. As much as I admire this, I find it alienating. She doesn’t ask for our love, she demands it.</p>
        <p class="cn">它很便宜，比较女性艺术家，但我想，在这种情况下，它是有意义的。凯莉散发着一切“所有”“麦当娜保留：宽恕，温暖，爱。这是一个明确的个人偏好，但我爱的力量来自一个悲伤或薄弱的地方。凯莉是在绝望的希望建立一个案例；麦当娜告诉我要有信心。麦当娜是一个强大的C所有的女性角色模型（和其他人）。但她是那么的控制，她甚至不需要我们。正如我欣赏，我觉得很疏远。她不向我们的爱，她要求。</p>
        <p class="en"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=cItHOl5LRWg" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="cn"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=cithol5lrwg" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="en">Yet, despite all of my private concerns about her art, I’m not an idiot. I know what the rest of the world is like. I feel compelled to take Madonna’s side if someone criticizes her. After all, most critiques of Madonna are lazily ageist or rockist, or even, still, sexist. The clich&eacute;d compliment of Madonna C she’s an “excellent business woman” C is one of the most awful back-handed compliments to lodge at a musician. And for many queers, hatred of pop is often a coded manifestation of the way the larger art world views the artistic work of homosexuals. Although many people agree that queers seem to be over-proportionally represented in the arts, their arts are often represented as being over-sophisticated or superficial. (The “real” art is still safely made by heterosexuals.) Pop music and the dance floor “where you can get away” give a lot of meaning to the lives of many (not all) queers, but since these euphorias are not integral to everyone, the meanings they hold can be dismissed as unreal or false. Madonna is on my side because she cares about a lot of the things I do.</p>
        <p class="cn">然而，尽管我对她的艺术的私人问题，我不是白痴。我知道世界上的其他国家一样。我觉得如果有人批评她把麦当娜的一面。毕竟，大多数批评麦当娜都懒洋洋地歧视或rockist，甚至，还有，性别歧视。这&eacute;d恭维的麦当娜C她是一个“优秀的商界女性”C是最可怕的一背手致意寄宿在一个音乐家。和许多同性恋者，仇恨的流行往往是一种方式的较大的艺术世界观的同性恋者的艺术作品编码的表现。尽管许多人认为同性恋者似乎在艺术成比例的代表，他们的艺术往往是过于复杂或表面。（“真实”的艺术仍然是安全的异性恋者。）流行音乐和跳舞”，你可以把“给很多很多人的生命的意义（不是全部）同性恋者，但由于这些euphorias不完整的人，他们持有的意义可以被解雇的不真实的或虚假的。麦当娜是在我身边，因为她关心许多事情我做。</p>
        <p class="en"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=vgeV23orVx0" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="cn"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=vgev23orvx0" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="en">This is why I can’t think about Madonna in any objective way. Sure, I don’t love her, but she’s been there, for me at key moments in my life. I watched the video premiere of “Material Girl” with my sister, I’ve partied countless times to “Hung Up,” I’ve finished off many nights of karaoke with “Like a Prayer.” I had my closeted teenage mind blown a teensy bit by watching the sexual possibilities (and hunky back-up dancers) of the video for “Human Nature.”</p>
        <p class="cn">这就是为什么我不想在任何客观的麦当娜。当然，我不爱她，但她在那里，在我的生命中的重要时刻。我看了“物质女孩”跟妹妹视频首映，我已经无数次“挂了，“我已经完成了许多夜晚唱卡拉ok”像祈祷。“我有我的密谈十几岁的脑子出了小小的一点看性别的可能性（和优秀的舞者）”的人性视频。”</p>
        <p class="en"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=GS6FCoq349o" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="cn"> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=gs6fcoq349o" target="_blank">youtube.com</a> </p>
        <p class="en">And I’ve spent several nights, on into morning, discussing the discography of Madonna with other gay men. Who likes “Cherish?” Who doesn’t like “Love Profusion”? “Hollywood”? What, in fact, do we do with <i>American Life</i> ? If nothing else, Madonna has given me something to argue with many other gay men about. She has given me a shorthand for talking about art and artistic choices, and for what art should mean to us.</p>
        <p class="cn">我花了几个晚上，到早晨，讨论麦当娜与其他***恋的唱片。谁喜欢“珍惜？“谁不喜欢“慷慨的爱”？“好莱坞”？什么，事实上，我们做着美国人的生活？如果没有别的，麦当娜已经给我的东西，跟其他许多同性恋者谈论。她给了我一个谈论艺术和艺术选择速记，和艺术应该对我们意味着什么。</p>
        <p class="en">I said that I couldn’t think about Madonna objectively. She is too immersed in my perception of pop, and the gay community’s perception of itself for me to be able to do that. But “objectivity” is a strange thing to cling to when talking about why music matters. No, I don’t love Madonna. But she’s been so much more important than that.</p>
        <p class="cn">我说，我不认为麦当娜客观。她太沉浸在我的感知的流行，和我能做自己同性恋社区的感知。但“客观性”是个奇怪的东西附着在谈到为什么音乐问题。不，我不喜欢麦当娜。但她是如此的比这更重要的。</p> 
       </div> 
       <div class="cn undis"> 
        <p><img src="http://s3-ec.buzzfed.com/static/enhanced/terminal05/2012/9/19/10/enhanced-buzz-790-1348064494-7.jpg" /></p>
        <p>音乐粉丝圈通常爆发的爱。但有时我们需要艺术家的出现不是一个浪漫的关系，但作为一个努力去理解，在我们的生活中一个令人难以置信的音乐力量。对我来说，这是麦当娜的力量。</p>
        <p>这很复杂。以“时尚，”为例。</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=gujqsaiodqi" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>“时尚”是一个典型的。麦当娜说，在那些冰冷的字符串和闪烁的鼓，她已经是难以置信的关键，这是她的不可动摇的自信，卖她的建议是永恒的开创性。如果你以前不酷和有趣，倾听“时尚”让你如此。难怪有那么多的病毒性视频孩子表演“时尚”：他们知道麦当娜可以直接注入与风格超越年龄的。</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=p7xooonftso" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=i8xdo4lsa10" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>这也难怪孩子们跳舞的视频似乎是同性恋，和这首歌是同性恋的人喜欢我特别鼓舞人心的歌。“时尚”是由voguing舞蹈风格的说出来，80年代酷儿球文化，是特色的纪录片，<a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.youtube.com/movie?v=a70zxs5snnm&amp;feature=mv_sr" target="_blank">paris is burning</a>严重影响。还有，嵌入在“时尚的”dna微妙的代码，尤其是对魅力和奢侈的强调。</p>
        <p>但这也有一个问题。大多数人谁发明了vogueing穷黑人和拉丁裔同性恋。“时尚”只是受到同性恋文化，或者是适当的？即使是巴黎的创造者是燃烧，珍妮利文斯顿，是因纠纷赔偿她的一些受试者起诉。当马尔科姆迈凯轮写了一首歌，由相同的球文化的影响（和之前的“时尚”），他以威利的忍者，一个原始的voguers。</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=a9kdmjqjs_0" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>麦当娜不包括任何原始voguers她的视频。麦当娜的球迷会说这不是重点。这首歌“时尚，”麦当娜偷偷插在主流的同性恋文化的一部分。马尔科姆迈凯轮的歌没有完成。麦当娜是不同文化之间的一座桥梁，他们会建议，这是所有她需要完成。当有这么少的同性恋文化可以在更广泛的文化，很难反驳这种观点。没有“时尚，“多数人不知道任何关于表演。</p>
        <p>麦当娜一直受到同性恋者因为她职业生涯的开始。她有她的第一场在天堂车库，在70年代和80年代纽约的同性恋社区的一个大俱乐部。在这段时间里，基思哈林，同性恋艺术家最出名的几何，涂鸦灵感的绘画作品，是<a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.gwarlingo.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/haring_polaroid-with-madonna-juxtapoz.jpg" target="_blank">one of her close friends</a>。在一个早期的突破表现在1984，麦当娜穿着哈林设计衣服当她唱他的天堂车库的生日聚会：</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=nrloyktvkl0" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>在她的视频和音乐会，她提出了替代性行为之前很久，凯蒂派瑞认为这是“尝试错误”。视频：“证明我的爱”是禁止显示什么今天将达到一个滑稽的驯服的量的同性接吻和角色扮演。尽管“***恋”已经成为一个毫无意义的词，如果有人仍然适合人，麦当娜是。</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=np_y740arei" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>同性恋者的反应。在一个同性恋俱乐部麦当娜的歌滴，看手起来。对我们许多人来说，这是有归属感的快乐：麦当娜以一种其他艺术家的图画。麦当娜记得我们是我们的，我们记得她C这也许是最强的一个同性恋图标是什么标识符。实现在一个俱乐部的每个人都感到非常相同的方式对一个艺术家你可以是一个强大的东西。即使现在，当部分的更广泛的文化仍然认为同性恋是困惑或不自然的，有关于自然C手在空中升起时，麦当娜的歌中的可预测性C放心和满意的东西。集体舞同情的女主角可以接近幸福。</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=edwb9jovrtu" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>但尽管如此，我不确定我爱她。作为一个同性恋，我有时觉得我一直喜欢麦当娜起草的我的性取向的情况下。麦当娜不是一个特别温暖的艺术家。麦当娜从未使我哭泣，当凯莉的“所有”“竟然对我做的最近的一天。</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=frv6fot1bni" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>它很便宜，比较女性艺术家，但我想，在这种情况下，它是有意义的。凯莉散发着一切“所有”“麦当娜保留：宽恕，温暖，爱。这是一个明确的个人偏好，但我爱的力量来自一个悲伤或薄弱的地方。凯莉是在绝望的希望建立一个案例；麦当娜告诉我要有信心。麦当娜是一个强大的C所有的女性角色模型（和其他人）。但她是那么的控制，她甚至不需要我们。正如我欣赏，我觉得很疏远。她不向我们的爱，她要求。</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=cithol5lrwg" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>然而，尽管我对她的艺术的私人问题，我不是白痴。我知道世界上的其他国家一样。我觉得如果有人批评她把麦当娜的一面。毕竟，大多数批评麦当娜都懒洋洋地歧视或rockist，甚至，还有，性别歧视。这&eacute;d恭维的麦当娜C她是一个“优秀的商界女性”C是最可怕的一背手致意寄宿在一个音乐家。和许多同性恋者，仇恨的流行往往是一种方式的较大的艺术世界观的同性恋者的艺术作品编码的表现。尽管许多人认为同性恋者似乎在艺术成比例的代表，他们的艺术往往是过于复杂或表面。（“真实”的艺术仍然是安全的异性恋者。）流行音乐和跳舞”，你可以把“给很多很多人的生命的意义（不是全部）同性恋者，但由于这些euphorias不完整的人，他们持有的意义可以被解雇的不真实的或虚假的。麦当娜是在我身边，因为她关心许多事情我做。</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=vgev23orvx0" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>这就是为什么我不想在任何客观的麦当娜。当然，我不爱她，但她在那里，在我的生命中的重要时刻。我看了“物质女孩”跟妹妹视频首映，我已经无数次“挂了，“我已经完成了许多夜晚唱卡拉ok”像祈祷。“我有我的密谈十几岁的脑子出了小小的一点看性别的可能性（和优秀的舞者）”的人性视频。”</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=gs6fcoq349o" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>我花了几个晚上，到早晨，讨论麦当娜与其他***恋的唱片。谁喜欢“珍惜？“谁不喜欢“慷慨的爱”？“好莱坞”？什么，事实上，我们做着美国人的生活？如果没有别的，麦当娜已经给我的东西，跟其他许多同性恋者谈论。她给了我一个谈论艺术和艺术选择速记，和艺术应该对我们意味着什么。</p>
        <p>我说，我不认为麦当娜客观。她太沉浸在我的感知的流行，和我能做自己同性恋社区的感知。但“客观性”是个奇怪的东西附着在谈到为什么音乐问题。不，我不喜欢麦当娜。但她是如此的比这更重要的。</p> 
       </div> 
       <div class="en undis"> 
        <p><img src="http://s3-ec.buzzfed.com/static/enhanced/terminal05/2012/9/19/10/enhanced-buzz-790-1348064494-7.jpg" /></p>
        <p>Music fandom usually erupts out of love. But sometimes we have connections to artists that emerge not as a romance, but as a struggle to understand an incredible musical force in our lives. For me, that force is Madonna.</p>
        <p>It’s complicated. Take “Vogue,” for instance.</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=GuJQSAiODqI" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>“Vogue” is a classic. Madonna asserts, over those icy strings and shimmering drums, that she has the key to being fabulous, and it’s her unshakeable poise that sells her advice as eternally groundbreaking. If you were not cool and interesting before, the act of listening to “Vogue” makes you so. No wonder there are so many viral videos of young kids voguing to “Vogue”: they knew Madonna could directly inject them with style beyond their years.</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=p7xooONFtso" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=I8XDo4lsa10" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>It’s also no wonder that the kids dancing to the video seem gay, and that the song has been a particularly inspiring anthem for gay people like me. “Vogue” was heavily influenced by the voguing dance style that came out of ‘80s queer ball culture and that was featured in the documentary <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.youtube.com/movie?v=a70ZXs5SnNM&amp;feature=mv_sr" target="_blank"><i>Paris is Burning</i></a>. There are subtle codes of queerness embedded in “Vogue’s” DNA, particularly in its emphasis on glamour and extravagance.</p>
        <p>But that’s also where there’s a problem. Most of the people who invented vogueing were poor black and Latino queers. Is “Vogue” just inspired by gay culture, or is it appropriated? Even the creator of <i>Paris is Burning</i>, Jennie Livingston, was sued by some of her subjects due to disputes over compensation. When Malcolm McLaren wrote a song influenced by the same ball culture (and predating “Vogue”), he featured Willie Ninja, one of the original voguers.</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=a9KDmJQjS_0" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>Madonna did not include any original voguers in her video. Madonna fans would say that this is beside the point. With the song “Vogue,” Madonna has sneakily inserted a part of gay culture in the mainstream. Malcolm McLaren’s song didn’t accomplish that. Madonna is a bridge between cultures, they’d suggest, and that’s all she needs to accomplish. When there is so little gay culture visible in the wider culture, it is difficult to argue against this point of view. Without “Vogue,” most people wouldn’t know anything about voguing.</p>
        <p>Madonna has been inspired by queers since the beginning of her career. She had some of her first performances at the Paradise Garage, a major club for New York’s gay community in the ‘70s and ‘80s. During this time, Keith Haring, the gay artist most known for his geometric, graffiti-inspired paintings, was <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.gwarlingo.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Haring_Polaroid-with-Madonna-Juxtapoz.jpg" target="_blank">one of her close friends</a>. In one early breakout performance in 1984, Madonna wore a Haring-designed outfit when she sang at his Paradise Garage birthday party:</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=nRlOyktvKL0" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>And in her videos and concerts she has presented alternative sexualities long before Katy Perry thought it was “so wrong” to try it. The video for “Justify My Love” was banned for showing what today would amount to a comically tame amount of same-sex kissing and role-playing. Although the term “gay icon” has become a meaningless term, if there is a person for whom it still fits, Madonna is it.</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=Np_Y740aReI" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>Queers have responded. Drop a Madonna song at a gay club, and watch the hands rise up. For many of us, there is a joy in this sense of ownership: Madonna is ours in a way that other artists aren’t. Madonna remembers us, and we remember her C and that’s perhaps the strongest identifier of what a gay icon is. Realizing that everyone at a club feels pretty much the same way you do about an artist can be a powerful thing. Even now, when parts of the wider culture still argue that homosexuals are confused or unnatural, there is something reassuring and satisfying about the predictability C the naturalness C of hands rising in the air when a Madonna song plays. Communally dancing to a sympathetic diva can be close to bliss.</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=EDwb9jOVRtU" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>But even with all of this, I’m not sure I love her. As a gay man, I sometimes feel like I’ve been drafted into liking Madonna by the circumstances of my sexuality. Madonna is not a particularly warm artist. Madonna has never made me cry, as Kylie’s “All the Lovers” unexpectedly did to me one day recently.</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=frv6FOt1BNI" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>It’s cheap comparing female artists, but I think, in this case, it makes sense. Kylie exudes everything in “All the Lovers” that Madonna withholds: forgiveness, warmth, love. And this is a definite personal preference, but I love when strength grows out of a place of sadness or weakness. Kylie is building a case for hope among the hopeless; Madonna tells me to be confident. Madonna is powerful and strong C a role model for all women (and many men). But she’s so in control she doesn’t even really need us. As much as I admire this, I find it alienating. She doesn’t ask for our love, she demands it.</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=cItHOl5LRWg" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>Yet, despite all of my private concerns about her art, I’m not an idiot. I know what the rest of the world is like. I feel compelled to take Madonna’s side if someone criticizes her. After all, most critiques of Madonna are lazily ageist or rockist, or even, still, sexist. The clich&eacute;d compliment of Madonna C she’s an “excellent business woman” C is one of the most awful back-handed compliments to lodge at a musician. And for many queers, hatred of pop is often a coded manifestation of the way the larger art world views the artistic work of homosexuals. Although many people agree that queers seem to be over-proportionally represented in the arts, their arts are often represented as being over-sophisticated or superficial. (The “real” art is still safely made by heterosexuals.) Pop music and the dance floor “where you can get away” give a lot of meaning to the lives of many (not all) queers, but since these euphorias are not integral to everyone, the meanings they hold can be dismissed as unreal or false. Madonna is on my side because she cares about a lot of the things I do.</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=vgeV23orVx0" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>This is why I can’t think about Madonna in any objective way. Sure, I don’t love her, but she’s been there, for me at key moments in my life. I watched the video premiere of “Material Girl” with my sister, I’ve partied countless times to “Hung Up,” I’ve finished off many nights of karaoke with “Like a Prayer.” I had my closeted teenage mind blown a teensy bit by watching the sexual possibilities (and hunky back-up dancers) of the video for “Human Nature.”</p>
        <p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=GS6FCoq349o" target="_blank">youtube.com</a></p>
        <p>And I’ve spent several nights, on into morning, discussing the discography of Madonna with other gay men. Who likes “Cherish?” Who doesn’t like “Love Profusion”? “Hollywood”? What, in fact, do we do with <i>American Life</i>? If nothing else, Madonna has given me something to argue with many other gay men about. She has given me a shorthand for talking about art and artistic choices, and for what art should mean to us.</p>
        <p>I said that I couldn’t think about Madonna objectively. She is too immersed in my perception of pop, and the gay community’s perception of itself for me to be able to do that. But “objectivity” is a strange thing to cling to when talking about why music matters. No, I don’t love Madonna. But she’s been so much more important than that.</p> 
       </div> 
      </div> 
